              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/258127/marcel-korpel&quot; title=&quot;21,315 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;Marcel Korpel&lt;/a&gt;
                &lt;/div&gt;
                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-date&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;comment-link&quot; href=&quot;#comment24457842_130323&quot;&gt;&lt;span title=&quot;2013-06-05 12:46:58Z, License: CC BY-SA 3.0&quot; class=&quot;relativetime-clean&quot;&gt;Jun 5, 2013 at 12:46&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;Because you limit the attack surface. If you sanitize early (when input), you have to be certain that there are no other holes in the application where bad data could enter through. Whereas if you do it late, then your output function doesn&apos;t have to &quot;trust&quot; that it is given safe data - it simply assumes that everything is unsafe.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
